    <body><div type="letter">
      <p>Southampton Tuesday Evening, 6th Octr</p>
      <p>My own dearest Willy. I have just had dinner, with the dear Hen, &amp; arrived here safely &amp; without adventure between 5 &amp; 6, having left Ockham at 1/2 past 10 this morning.-- I am not tired, &amp; am very well.-- I took my soup at Alsford, &amp; had a nice walk there up to the Church.-- My only grievance is that my face is burnt</p>
      <p>paradoxical as this may sound with the cold air, &amp; is as red as the Red Lion of High Wycombe, which is not becoming.-- When you come through Alsford, remember that the Bird hopped about there. The poor little thing almost cried last night, when it found itself alone in bed. I will be better tonight, because its Hen is in the house with it, &amp; that is next best to its Cock.-- How handsome you looked when I left you yesterday on your gallant steed!</p>
      <p>The bird was proud of you.--</p>
      <p>I fear the dear Hen is not so well recovered from her cold as I had hoped. She still has much of a little cough which I am too well acquainted with in her.--</p>
      <p>The young man whom I mentioned to you as desirable in the place of the lesser of your two dismissed ones, is looking out for such a situation, &amp; would be too glad to come. He behaved extremely well in Mama's family, &amp; is a very industrious hard-working youth.-- Shall I write</p>
      <p>about him?-- Let me know by return of post, please.--</p>
      <p>I read a deal of Rob Roy in the carriage today.--</p>
      <p>I feel the want of your sweet voice &amp; black eyes, sadly-- more even than I had expected.--</p>
      <p>Do not be vexed with the poor Bird's expression of affection.--</p>
      <p>My dearest, I will write to you more at length tomorrow.--</p>
      <p>Most affecy The Little Bird A. A. King</p>
    </div></body>
